originalText.text: I use to live their when I was born and the location was the best place because they got the view of the East River surround the Williamsburg Bridge. They had the best neighbors at the time. The subway station was not that far away and they have F, J, M, and Z train to Delancey Street/Essex Street Station. Too bad we had to move out in 2005 and I miss that place so much and one day I will visit the place someday.

originalText.text: Currently a lot of construction going on in response to hurricane Sandy  that caused flooding in the area. Generators are being placed on the roofs of these developments so the residents don't experience another repeat of Sandy.

originalText.text: The Sandy Recovery upgrade project, though seemingly necessary, has been an ongoing execution. The entire complex grounds are dug up. Narrow paths are created by building entrances to funnel tenants out along the ever-changing walking paths. Garbage is dropped in open construction pits aggravating an already fruitful rat population. While visiting I saw one of the contractors toss his apple core on the sidewalk after he finished with it. I never know which way to walk, because paths are gated and frequently changed. This is a deathtrap in case of a fire or any other emergency. At the least, it is a confusing journey around the complex for anyone of sound mind..or not. I can only imagine that this project would have been executed differently if it had affected a different demographic

originalText.text: They need to control the rats and roaches. The kitchens need to be modernized.  The staff is 5 star. It's not fair that the staff cleans the elevators then people leave their garbage on the floor, there should be monitored camera surveillance to see whom does it and fine them.They do it again double the fine. The garbage should not be put right out front as it causes the rats to clutter there. Extermination  should be done once a month. This will help the roach and rat problem
